window.docContents[175].resolve({"/Basic-Types/Arrays/#subarray":{"contents":"Subarray α 类型是 Std.Slice α 的缩写。\n这意味着，除了本节中的运算符之外，通用字段表示法还可用于调用 Std.Slice 命名空间中的函数，例如 Std.Slice.foldl。\n\nA region of some underlying array.A subarray contains an array together with the start and end indices of a region of interest.\nSubarrays can be used to avoid copying or allocating space, while being more convenient than\ntracking the bounds by hand. The region of interest consists of every index that is both greater\nthan or equal to start and strictly less than stop.\n\nThe empty subarray.This empty subarray is backed by an empty array.\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n","context":"Lean 参考\u0009基本类型\u0009储备","header":"20.16.5. 子储备","id":"/Basic-Types/Arrays/#subarray"},"/Basic-Types/Natural-Numbers/#nat-api-predicates":{"contents":"Non-strict, or weak, inequality of natural numbers, usually accessed via the ≤ operator.Non-strict inequality is reflexive: n ≤ nIf n ≤ m, then n ≤ m + 1.\n\nStrict inequality of natural numbers, usually accessed via the < operator.It is defined as n < m = n + 1 ≤ m.\n\n","context":"Lean 参考\u0009基本类型\u0009自然数\u0009API 参考\u0009比较","header":"20.1.4.5.3. 谓词","id":"/Basic-Types/Natural-Numbers/#nat-api-predicates"},"/Error-Explanations/About___-___redundantMatchAlt___/#zh-errorexplanations-redundantmatchalt-root":{"contents":"\n\n当永远无法达到模式匹配中的替代值时，就会发生此错误：任何可能会出现的值\n匹配提供的模式也将匹配一些前面的替代方案。请参阅\n模式匹配 手册部分了解更多详细信息\n关于模式匹配。\n\n此错误可能出现在任何模式匹配表达式中，包括\nmatch 表达式、方程函数定义、if let\n绑定，以及带有后备子句的一元 let 绑定。\n\n在多臂模式匹配中，如果不太具体的模式出现在\n它所包含的更具体的一项。请记住，表达式与来自的模式相匹配\n从上到下，因此特定模式应先于通用模式。\n\n在 if let 绑定和带有后备的一元 let 绑定中\n子句中，仅指定了一种模式，此错误表明指定的模式\n总是会匹配的。在这种情况下，有问题的绑定可以替换为标准\n模式匹配let。\n\n导致此错误的一个常见原因是用于匹配构造函数的模式是\n相反，解释为变量绑定。例如，如果构造函数\n名称（例如，cons）在该类型的命名空间之外写入时没有前缀（List）。\n默认情况下启用的构造函数名称作为变量 linter 将在任何变量上显示警告\n类似于构造函数名称的模式。\n\n此错误几乎总是表明出现该错误的代码存在问题。不过，如果需要的话，\nset_option match.ignoreUnusedAlts true 将禁用对此错误的检查并允许模式\n与通过丢弃未使用的臂来编译的冗余替代品进行匹配。\n\n\n\n","context":"Lean 参考\u0009错误说明","header":"关于： redundantMatchAlt","id":"/Error-Explanations/About___-___redundantMatchAlt___/#zh-errorexplanations-redundantmatchalt-root"},"/Functors___-Monads-and-___do___-Notation/Varieties-of-Monads/#reader-monad":{"contents":"Reader monads provide the ability to implicitly thread a value through a computation. The value can\nbe read, but not written. A MonadWithReader ρ instance additionally allows the value to be locally\noverridden for a sub-computation.In this class, ρ is an outParam, which means that it is inferred from m. MonadReaderOf ρ\nprovides the same operations, but allows ρ to influence instance synthesis.Retrieves the local value.Use readThe to explicitly specify a type when more than one value is available.\n\nReader monads provide the ability to implicitly thread a value through a computation. The value can\nbe read, but not written. A MonadWithReader ρ instance additionally allows the value to be locally\noverridden for a sub-computation.In this class, ρ is a semiOutParam, which means that it can influence the choice of instance.\nMonadReader ρ provides the same operations, but requires that ρ be inferable from m.Retrieves the local value.\n\nRetrieves the local value whose type is ρ.  This is useful when a monad supports reading more than\none type of value.Use read for a version that expects the type ρ to be inferred from m.\n\nA reader monad that additionally allows the value to be locally overridden.In this class, ρ is an outParam, which means that it is inferred from m. MonadWithReaderOf ρ\nprovides the same operations, but allows ρ to influence instance synthesis.Locally modifies the reader monad's value while running an action.During the inner action x, reading the value returns f applied to the original value. After\ncontrol returns from x, the reader monad's value is restored.\n\nA reader monad that additionally allows the value to be locally overridden.In this class, ρ is a semiOutParam, which means that it can influence the choice of instance.\nMonadWithReader ρ provides the same operations, but requires that ρ be inferable from m.Locally modifies the reader monad's value while running an action.During the inner action x, reading the value returns f applied to the original value. After\ncontrol returns from x, the reader monad's value is restored.\n\nLocally modifies the reader monad's value while running an action, with the reader monad's local\nvalue type specified explicitly. This is useful when a monad supports reading more than one type of\nvalue.During the inner action x, reading the value returns f applied to the original value. After\ncontrol returns from x, the reader monad's value is restored.Use withReader for a version that expects the local value's type to be inferred from m.\n\nAdds the ability to access a read-only value of type ρ to a monad. The value can be locally\noverridden by withReader, but it cannot be mutated.Actions in the resulting monad are functions that take the local value as a parameter, returning\nordinary actions in m.\n\nA monad with access to a read-only value of type ρ. The value can be locally overridden by\nwithReader, but it cannot be mutated.\n\nExecutes an action from a monad with a read-only value in the underlying monad m.\n\nRetrieves the reader monad's local value. Typically accessed via read, or via readThe when more\nthan one local value is available.\n\nModifies a reader monad's local value with f. The resulting computation applies f to the\nincoming local value and passes the result to the inner computation.\n\nReturns the provided value a, ignoring the reader monad's local value. Typically used via\nPure.pure.\n\nSequences two reader monad computations. Both are provided with the local value, and the second is\npassed the value of the first. Typically used via the >>= operator.\n\nRecovers from errors. The same local value is provided to both branches. Typically used via the\n<|> operator.\n\nFails with a recoverable error.\n\n","context":"Lean 参考\u0009函子、Monad 和  do  表示法\u0009单子的种类","header":"18.5.5. 读者","id":"/Functors___-Monads-and-___do___-Notation/Varieties-of-Monads/#reader-monad"},"/Notations-and-Macros/Defining-New-Syntax/#syntax-construction-helpers":{"contents":"Creates an identifier from a name. The resulting identifier has no source position.\n\nCreates an identifier with its position copied from src.To refer to a specific constant without a risk of variable capture, use mkCIdentFrom instead.\n\nCreates an identifier with its position copied from the syntax returned by getRef.To refer to a specific constant without a risk of variable capture, use mkCIdentFromRef instead.\n\nCreates an identifier that refers to a constant c. The identifier has no source position.This variant of mkIdent makes sure that the identifier cannot accidentally be captured.\n\nCreates an identifier referring to a constant c. The identifier's position is copied from src.This variant of mkIdentFrom makes sure that the identifier cannot accidentally be captured.\n\nCreates an identifier referring to a constant c. The identifier's position is copied from the\nsyntax returned by getRef.This variant of mkIdentFrom makes sure that the identifier cannot accidentally be captured.\n\nCreates syntax representing a Lean term application, but avoids degenerate empty applications.\n\nCreates syntax representing a Lean constant application, but avoids degenerate empty applications.\n\nCreates a literal of the given kind. It is the caller's responsibility to ensure that the provided\nliteral is a valid atom for the provided kind.If info is provided, then the literal's source information is copied from it.\n\nCreates literal syntax for the given character.If info is provided, then the literal's source information is copied from it.\n\nCreates literal syntax for the given string.If info is provided, then the literal's source information is copied from it.\n\nCreates literal syntax for a number, which is provided as a string. The caller must ensure that the\nstring is a valid token for the num token parser.If info is provided, then the literal's source information is copied from it.\n\nCreates literal syntax for a natural number.If info is provided, then the literal's source information is copied from it.\n\nCreates literal syntax for a number in scientific notation. The caller must ensure that the provided\nstring is a valid scientific notation literal.If info is provided, then the literal's source information is copied from it.\n\nCreates literal syntax for a name. The caller must ensure that the provided string is a valid name\nliteral.If info is provided, then the literal's source information is copied from it.\n\nCreates an optional node.Optional nodes consist of null nodes that contain either zero or one element.\n\nCreates a group node, as if it were parsed by Lean.Parser.group.\n\nCreates a hole (_). The hole's position is copied from ref.\n\n\n\n","context":"Lean 参考\u0009符号和宏\u0009定义新语法","header":"23.4.9. 构造语法的助手","id":"/Notations-and-Macros/Defining-New-Syntax/#syntax-construction-helpers"}});